US Megadrought: More Water Reductions Mandated in Seven States 

Water usage from the Colorado river could be slapped with a 30% limit after the states failed to meet a federal deadline to reduce consumption - that’s as the region suffers its driest 22-year spell in 1,200 years. 

Water levels at Lake Powell and Lake Mead - supplied by the river and crucial for the generation of hydroelectricity- are “dangerously low”, according to officials. If they drop further, millions of people could face power cuts. 

“The bureau is asking institutions … to do something drastic in a few months. States have been given 60 days to come up with more than twice the cuts that they agreed to,” said author and former water manager Eric Kuhn.
